  "prompt": "Why is the word wrap feature not a default in Notepad?",
  "response": "The lack of word wrap as a default in Notepad is largely due to historical reasons and Microsoft's design philosophy for the text editor. Here are a few key points:\n\n1. Historical Design\n- Notepad was originally designed as a simple, lightweight text editor for basic tasks\n- Early versions prioritized plain text editing and coding compatibility\n- Word wrap was seen as unnecessary for technical users and programmers\n\n2. Technical Considerations\n- Non-wrapped text allows precise line-by-line editing\n- Programmers and developers often prefer seeing exact line breaks\n- Maintaining original text formatting is important for some file types\n\n3. Simplicity\n- Microsoft wanted to keep Notepad minimal and straightforward\n- Adding word wrap was considered an optional feature\n- Users can easily enable word wrap from the \"Format\" menu\n\n4. Compatibility\n- Non-wrapped text ensures consistent display across different applications\n- Preserves original line breaks in source code and configuration files\n\n5. Legacy Reasons\n- Maintaining consistency with older versions of the software\n- Backwards compatibility with user expectations\n\nIn modern versions of Notepad (Windows 10 and 11), word wrap can be easily enabled through the menu, addressing many user preferences while maintaining the original design philosophy.",
